  <subsection>
    <title>Preview of Orders of Magnitude</title>
    <p>
      Below is a table that describes some large numbers in words, standard decimal notation, and scientific notation.  Notice how scientific notation keeps track of the number of decimal places to the right of the first digit, but before the decimal point.  Keeping track of the number of decimal places in quantities can be useful for some estimation problems.  Recall that if a number does not have a decimal point displayed, then the decimal point is assumed to be at the right end of the number.
    </p>
    <table>
      <tabular left="minor" top="minor">
        <col right="minor" width="15%" />
        <col right="minor" width="20%" />
        <col right="minor" width="5%" />
        <col right="minor" width="60%" />
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><b>Skill or Concept: I can...</b></cell>
          <cell><b>Rating from 1 to 5</b></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>One hunderd twenty-two and one tenth</cell>
          <cell>122.1</cell>
          <cell><m>1.221 \times 10^2</m></cell>
          <cell>2</cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>One thousand forty-five</cell>
          <cell>1,045</cell>
          <cell><m>1.045 \times 10^3</m></cell>
          <cell>3</cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>
            <line>Three million, four hundred seventy five</line>
            <line>thousand, three hundred twenty and</line>
            <line>seventy-one hundredths</line>
          </cell>
          <cell>3,475,320.71</cell>
          <cell><m>3.47532071 \times 10^6</m></cell>
          <cell>6</cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>
            <line>One billion, four hundred seventy-two</line>
            <line>million, three hundred forty-one thousand,</line>
            <line>nine hundred eighty-two and three tenths</line>
          </cell>
          <cell>1,472,341,982.30</cell>
          <cell><m>1.4723419823 \times 10^9</m></cell>
          <cell>9</cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>One trillion</cell>
          <cell>1,000,000,000,000</cell>
          <cell><m>1 \times 10^{12}</m></cell>
          <cell>12</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <p>
      The number of places you would move the decimal point in order to put a number in scientific notation can be used to describe the size of the number.  If the decimal point would be moved 6 places we say that number is <q>in the millions.</q>  If the decimal point would be moved 10 places we say the number is <q>in the tens of billions.</q>
    </p>
    <p>
      To estimate with large numbers, we often round to a convenient place and then add or multiply the number as required.  Recall that if we round the number 145 to the ten's place we get 150, but if we round 145 to the hundred's place we get 100.  (If we rounded to the ten's and then rounded to the hundred's we would get a different answer: 200).
    </p>
    <p>
      For example, suppose we wanted a quick estimate of the yearly total expenses for a project in China that is expected to cost approximately \$10 for every person in the country per day.  By using estimates, we may be able to perform the calculations by hand reasonably quickly, as follows, to obtain a rough answer.  We could estimate the population of China as 1.5 billion, use the ten dollars per person, and estimate the number of days in a year as 350.  The product of these three numbers is
    </p>
    <me>
      350 \times 10 \times 1.5 \times 10^9
    </me>
    <p>
      If we leave off the <m>10^9</m> we get
    </p>
    <me>= 350 \times 15</me>
    <p>
      which is 10 times 350 plus another half of that: $3500 + 1750 = 5250$, so now we have
    </p>
    <me>
      5250 \times 10^9
    </me>
    <p>
      which is 5,250 billion or 5.25 trillion.  The simpler description is 5.25 trillion.
    </p>
    <p>
      Recall that, when we say something like <q><m>\text{5,250} \times 10^9</m> is 5.250 billion</q> we are using these facts:
    </p>
    <table>
      <tabular halign="center" left="medium" top="medium">
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell left="medium" right="medium">
            Number
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            Power of Ten
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            Words
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell left="medium" right="medium">
            1,000
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            <m>10^3</m>
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            Thousand
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell left="medium" right="medium">
            1,000,000
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            <m>10^6</m>
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            Million
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell left="medium" right="medium">
            1,000,000,000
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            <m> 10^9</m>
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            Billion
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell left="medium" right="medium">
            1,000,000,000,000
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            <m>10^{12}</m>
          </cell>
          <cell right="medium">
            Trillion
          </cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </subsection>

  <worksheet xml:id="preview-billions">
    <title>Preview Orders of Magnitude</title>
    <objectives>
      <ul>
        <li>Estimate orders of magnitude</li>
        <li>Calculate unit conversions</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
    <page>
      <p>
        Use the above estimation strategy, together with an others you are familiar with, to decide if the following quantities are in the millions, billions, trillions, or some other size, such as tens of millions. (<b>Note:</b>} For some of these questions you could find the exact values, but for others, such as populations, any number would be an estimate.)
      </p>
      <exercise xml:id="estimate-seconds" workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          The number of seconds you have been alive.
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="estimate-college-money" workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          The amount of money needed to send all adults in the United States to college for four years.  Assume there are 200 million adults in the United States.
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="estimate-lord-of-the-rings" workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          The number of words in the Lord of the Rings trilogy.
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </page>

    <page>
      <p>
        Refine your above estimates by using a calculator and obtaining any missing information you need from the internet.
      </p>
      <exercise xml:id="calculate-seconds" workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          The number of seconds you have been alive. For example, for a 10-year-old: <m>60 \times 60 \times 24 \times 365 \times 10 = 315,360,000</m> or about 315 million seconds.
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="calculate-college-money" workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          The amount of money needed to send all adults in the United States to college for four years.  Estimate yearly tuition to be about 17,000.  Again, assume there are about 200 million adults in the United States.
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="calculate-lord-of-the-rings" workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          The number of words in Lord of the Rings trilogy. Using an internet search, we found that a sample page of Lord of the Rings has about 300 words on it, and the series is 1,008 pages long.
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        You should be able to do the following things for the next class.  Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1-5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).
      </p>
      
      Before beginning lesson 1.2, you should understand the concepts and demonstrate the skills listed below:
      <table>
        <tabular left="minor" top="minor">
          <col right="minor" width="80%" />
          <col right="minor" width="20%" />
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><b>Skill or Concept: I can...</b></cell>
            <cell><b>Rating from 1 to 5</b></cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell>convert between millions, billions, and trillions</cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell>compute basic percentages and ratios.</cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell>
              express one number as a percent of another.
            </cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </page>
  </worksheet>